hands_on_practices.solution:
We are given a global holomorphic frame for a rank-2 bundle over the unit disc $\mathbb{D}$. The Chern connection matrix $\theta$ in a holomorphic frame is given by the formula $\theta = (\partial H) H^{-1}$, where $H$ is the matrix of the Hermitian metric. The curvature is then given by $F = d\theta + \theta \wedge \theta$.

The given metric matrix is
$$
H = \begin{pmatrix}
h_{11} & 0 \\
0 & h_{22}
\end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix}
\exp(\beta z + \overline{\beta}\bar{z}) & 0 \\
0 & \exp(\alpha z\bar{z} + \delta z^2 + \overline{\delta}\bar{z}^2)
\end{pmatrix}
$$
Since $H$ is diagonal, its inverse is simply the matrix of reciprocal diagonal entries:
$$
H^{-1} = \begin{pmatrix}
h_{11}^{-1} & 0 \\
0 & h_{22}^{-1}
\end{pmatrix}
$$
Next, we apply the operator $\partial = dz \, \frac{\partial}{\partial z}$ to $H$:
$$
\partial H = \begin{pmatrix}
\partial h_{11} & 0 \\
0 & \partial h_{22}
\end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix}
\beta h_{11} dz & 0 \\
0 & (\alpha\bar{z} + 2\delta z) h_{22} dz
\end{pmatrix}
$$
Now we compute the connection matrix $\theta$:
$$
\theta = (\partial H) H^{-1} = \begin{pmatrix}
\beta h_{11} dz & 0 \\
0 & (\alpha\bar{z} + 2\delta z) h_{22} dz
\end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix}
h_{11}^{-1} & 0 \\
0 & h_{22}^{-1}
\end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix}
\beta dz & 0 \\
0 & (\alpha\bar{z} + 2\delta z) dz
\end{pmatrix}
$$
The curvature matrix is $F = d\theta + \theta \wedge \theta$. Since the base manifold is a complex curve (dimension 1), any wedge product of two (1,0)-forms like $dz \wedge dz$ is zero. As $\theta$ is a matrix of (1,0)-forms, the term $\theta \wedge \theta$ vanishes identically.
Thus, the curvature simplifies to $F = d\theta$.
The exterior derivative is $d = \partial + \bar{\partial}$. Since $\theta$ is a matrix of (1,0)-forms, $\partial\theta$ would be a matrix of (2,0)-forms, which is also zero on a complex curve. Therefore, $F = \bar{\partial}\theta$.
We apply $\bar{\partial} = d\bar{z} \, \frac{\partial}{\partial\bar{z}}$ to each component of $\theta$:
$$
F_{11} = \bar{\partial}(\beta dz) = \frac{\partial \beta}{\partial \bar{z}} d\bar{z} \wedge dz = 0 \quad (\text{since } \beta \text{ is constant})
$$
$$
F_{22} = \bar{\partial}((\alpha\bar{z} + 2\delta z)dz) = \frac{\partial}{\partial\bar{z}}(\alpha\bar{z} + 2\delta z) \, d\bar{z} \wedge dz = \alpha \, d\bar{z} \wedge dz
$$
Using the standard orientation $dz \wedge d\bar{z} = - d\bar{z} \wedge dz$, we have $F_{22} = -\alpha \, dz \wedge d\bar{z}$.
The off-diagonal terms of $\theta$ are zero, so their derivatives are also zero. The curvature matrix is:
$$
F = \begin{pmatrix}
0 & 0 \\
0 & -\alpha \, dz \wedge d\bar{z}
\end{pmatrix}
$$
A connection is unitary flat if and only if its curvature $F$ is identically zero. This requires $F_{22}=0$, which implies $\alpha=0$. The values of $\beta$ and $\delta$ do not affect the curvature.

Finally, we find the scalar function $U(z,\bar{z})$ from the relation $\mathrm{tr}(F) = U(z,\bar{z})\,dz \wedge d\bar{z}$.
$$
\mathrm{tr}(F) = F_{11} + F_{22} = 0 - \alpha \, dz \wedge d\bar{z} = -\alpha \, dz \wedge d\bar{z}
$$
Comparing this with the definition, we identify $U(z,\bar{z}) = -\alpha$. The flatness condition $F=0$ is equivalent to $U(z,\bar{z})=0$, i.e., $\alpha=0$.
